metadata.name: Keep On #93
metadata.description:
One year ago, I published my first Fx(hash) work, "Finding my way". This piece marks its anniversary, and is intended as a THANK YOU to all the people that collected my works. 

It is based on the same algorithm as "Finding my way", i.e. a line growth animated process based on Substrate (Jared Tarbell, 2003) guided by dynamically changing vector fields made with trigonometric functions, but it uses different palettes, more vector fields, and a few more tweakings of the algorithm parameters.

The original piece was intended to symbolise a person's process of finding her/his way. Upon further reflections on the result, I think it more as representing a community process. So here is my wish for the Fx(hash) community, let's keep on finding our way.   

In what now could become a tradition, I've stolen again a palette from the beautiful work of Iskra Velitchkova.

Implemented using various packages from thi.ng/umbrella by Karsten Schmidt, AKA Toxi

metadata.name: CRAYONS #101
metadata.description:
Sometimes we like the feeling of being citizens of the places we visit. Our senses adapt to capture in detail the signs of the environment. It is then when we begin to breathe the color that surrounds us and places us in that unique setting.

This is how this inspired collection is born and grows, the colors that enchant us as children on a sheet of paper and now serve to paint every place we visit.

The 6 color palettes of this collection aim to transport us to all those places.

Paris: Its pastel tones strolling along the Trocadero on the banks of the Seine.

Berlin: How to tell the story with color in the graffiti of the East Side Gallery and the wall.

Mexico: Its flavor is in the rainbow of its embroideries, alebrijes and altars.

Kenya: Sunrises and sunsets that impregnate the retina with the tones of the savannah.

Costa Rica: Pure life, pure green, from gentle to intense Monte Lluvioso.

Colombia: Seas of flowers flood the streets with colors and aromas celebrating the Feria De Las Flores

High-resolution png downloads are available by pressing number keys 1 (3000px), 2 (6000px), or 3 (9000px).

metadata.name: DOM #55
metadata.description:
From Proto-Indo-European *dṓm (“house, home”), from root *dem- (“to build”).

The humans use of stone in architecture and housing dates back to the dawn of civilisation, where its excellence in material, ecological and aesthetic qualities recalls the original concept of home, intended as a shelter from the external world.
The word Home is more representing of the true meaning of DOM as it is tied to the sense of family, homeland and provenance. The place where the heart is.

As a continuation of my personal generative art journey, the DOM is a natural sequel and a closer, much deeper & intimate look to Voyage background ancient cities/ villages architecture and typical stone houses. Inspired by Dalmatia coastal & Herzegovina hinterland but you will hopefully find your own dream home.

Thank You!


Press ‘s’ to save canvas or ‘2’ for 2x and ‘4’ for 4x image resolution png
Created with love for pure p5js and generative art

@Qotonana
February, 2023.

metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #347
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.name: Automatic #179
metadata.description:
Cellular automata is fascinating :) Applications ranging from physics and biology to modeling and architecture, with artistic and aesthetic representation always following along. Perfect example for emergence, how simple even byte-size rules result in complex structures, forming patterns and unpredictable behaviors...

This one is simple, 1d elementary cellular automata and the 256 rules as the foundation, where each iteration consists of the following elements: base rules - 3 are selected and allocated into the start row compositions, a set of shapes is assigned to a grid of various sizes. Occasionally, dynamic rule set is added - where a rule is randomly transformed into another random rule on a random row of the grid. A vertical or horizontal alignment of the grid is chosen an a color set assigned. Sometimes, a simple 2d noise is applied to lighten (or well, darken) things a bit. The grid is finite and confined by the amount of cells in a row and amount of rows fitting the canvas given cell size.

The properties are recorded as features, more as a reference to the building blocks, rather then rarity indication. Probably be best viewed in live mode :)

Pressing 's' in live mode will save the png of the output.
